# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# combined — __getitem__, __setitem__, __delitem__ across all 10 asyncio subjects
#
# Covers the full matrix: 10 classes x 3 methods = 30 rows.
# __getitem__: false for all 10 — obj[key] protocol not in own __dict__.
# __setitem__: false for all 10 — obj[key]=val protocol not in own __dict__.
# __delitem__: false for all 10 — del obj[key] protocol not in own __dict__.
# All 30 values are false.
# asyncio types are designed for coroutine-based concurrency — their entire
#   API surface is expressed through await, async with, async for, and explicit
#   method calls. The container/mapping access protocol dunders (__getitem__,
#   __setitem__, __delitem__) are not overridden in the Python-level __dict__
#   of any of the 10 types.
# asyncio.Queue/PriorityQueue/LifoQueue note: although these types store items
#   in an internal data structure, access is mediated exclusively through
#   get()/put() coroutines and qsize()/empty()/full() methods. None of the
#   three queue types define __getitem__, __setitem__, or __delitem__ in their
#   own __dict__.
# asyncio.Future note: Future manages a state machine (PENDING/RUNNING/
#   CANCELLED/FINISHED) and a result slot, but neither the state nor the
#   result is accessible via subscript. None of __getitem__, __setitem__, or
#   __delitem__ is defined in Future.__dict__.
# asyncio.Event note: Event manages a boolean flag via set()/clear()/is_set();
#   even though it has a logical boolean state, none of __getitem__, __setitem__,
#   or __delitem__ is defined in asyncio.Event.__dict__.
# asyncio.Semaphore/BoundedSemaphore note: the permit counter is encapsulated
#   behind acquire()/release() coroutines; no container/mapping protocol dunders
#   are defined in their __dict__.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

